eexamine and redefine the legal construction of freedom, will, and consent. This study places such historically central anti-slavery figures as Frederick Douglass, Olaudah Equiano, and William Lloyd Garrison alongside such lesser-known slave plaintiffs as Lucy Ann Delaney, Grace, Catharine Linda, Med, and Harriet Robinson Scott. Situated at the confluence of literary criticism, feminism, and legal history, Neither Fugitive nor Free presents the freedom suit as a "new" genre to African American and American literary studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAntislavery movementsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlacksxTravelxHistoryx19th century. 0aBlacksxTravelxHistoryy19th century. 0aLaw and literaturexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aLaw and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLaw in literature. 0aSlave narrativesxHistory and criticism. 0aSlavery in literature. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aSlavesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxTravelxHistoryx19th century. 0aSlavesxTravelxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh  aAfrican.  aAmerican.  aFree.  aFugitive.  aNeither.  aSituated.  aconfluence.  acriticism.  afeminism.  afreedom.  agenre.  ahistory.  alegal.  aliterary.  anew.  apresents.  astud